	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>High commodity prices here to stay, but at lower levels than recent peaks</h1>

			
			<h4>
												09 August 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>According to the latest OECD–FAO agricultural outlook for 2011–2020, ‘a good harvest in the coming months should push commodity prices down from the extreme levels seen earlier this year.’ It adds however that ‘over the coming decade real prices for cereals could average as much as 20 percent higher and those for meats as much as 30 percent higher, compared to 2001-10’. These price levels would still be below ‘the peak price levels experienced in 2007-08 and again this year’.</p><p>The report notes a fifth successive year of high price volatility. It was considered that the production response to rising prices would be conditioned by ‘the relative cost of inputs’ and the rate of transmission of price increases along supply chains to producers. The report notes the slower rate of productivity growth as a source of concern. ‘Global agricultural production is projected to grow at 1.7% annually, on average, compared to 2.6% in the previous decade.’</p><p>The report considers that ‘per capita food consumption will expand most rapidly in Eastern Europe, Asia and Latin America where incomes are rising and population growth is slowing.’ The fastest growth in trade will come from ‘emerging exporters in Eastern Europe, Central Asia and Latin American countries’, while ‘growing food deficits are expected in Sub-Saharan countries as population driven demand outpaces rising domestic production’.</p><p>On biofuels, the report considers that ‘the use of agricultural output as feedstock for biofuels will continue its robust growth, largely driven by biofuel mandates and support policies’, with ‘an estimated 13% of global coarse grain production, 15% of vegetable oil production and 30% of sugar cane production’ being used in biofuel production by 2020.</p><p>Overall the report highlights eight key factors driving price volatility: weather and climate change; stock levels; energy prices; exchange rates; growing demand; resource pressures; trade restrictions; and speculation. According to the report, ‘weather-related crop yield variations are expected to become an even more critical driver of price volatility in the future.’</p><p>While high prices are seen as raising a major challenge in terms of food insecurity, they are also seen as creating ‘major opportunities for food and agricultural producers’. The key policy challenge is seen as promoting productivity growth, ‘particularly for small producers’ in order to:</p>
<ul>

<li>improve market resilience to external shocks;</li>

<li>reduce waste;</li>

<li>increase ‘supplies to local markets at affordable prices’.</li>

</ul>
<p>The report maintains that ‘public sector investments are required in agricultural research and development, institutions and infrastructure to increase sector productivity and resilience towards weather/climate change and resource scarcity.’</p><p>The importance of enhancing market transparency and assisting the most vulnerable through social safety nets is also recognised, including through the establishment of ‘emergency food reserves for targeted assistance to poor people’.</p><p>Rising food prices are seen as threatening economic stability in some developing countries. OECD Secretary-General Angel Gurría called on governments to ‘improve information and transparency of both physical and financial markets, encourage investments that increase productivity in developing countries, remove production and trade distorting policies and assist the vulnerable to better manage risk and uncertainty.’ FAO Director-General Jacques Diouf identified ‘boosting investment in agriculture and reinforcing rural development in developing countries’ as the key to helping those most at risk.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
FAO, ‘Higher agriculture commodity prices here to stay’, 17 June 2011<br/>

<a href="http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/80345/icode/" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/news/story/en/item/80345/icode/</a> <br/>
OECD–FAO, ‘OECD - FAO agricultural outlook 2011-2020’, June 2011<br/>
<a href="http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/user_upload/newsroom/docs/Outlookflyer.pdf" target="_self">http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/user_upload/newsroom/docs/Outlookflyer.pdf</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>For a number of ACP governments, the prospect of the real prices for cereals and meat being 20% and 30% higher than the average of the previous decade comes against the background of the erosion of the value of trade preferences for traditional export commodities. In some regions this may require a fundamental rethink of the orientation of agricultural policy, towards increased support for domestic production for domestic markets (e.g. in the Caribbean). It will also require a review of land policies, which in recent years have seen the allocation of land to foreign-owned, export-oriented agricultural production companies (e.g. in Africa).</p><p>Given the fiscal constraints facing ACP governments, this may throw up some acute policy dilemmas and even generate conflicts of interest, as traditional patterns of government expenditure and incentives shift towards increasing production for local markets and away from supporting production of primary commodities for export. In some regions this could be eased, if mechanisms could be found to effectively deliver ‘aid for trade’ support to improving the productivity of smallholder farming.</p><p>Issues related to the use of traditional trade-policy tools, some of which may throw up contradictions with the trajectory of certain IEPA provisions, are also likely to arise.</p><p>The emerging situation will require a careful and realistic analysis of which products generate the greatest net foreign-exchange savings/earnings and have the greatest impact on local employment creation. These may not be the same products as those which have traditionally been produced.</p>
		</div>
		
